 "cells": [

   "id": "8f77b0b3-6850-48cc-99c1-e45229e9765a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Dynamic Pharmacophores\n",
    "\n",
    "Dynamic pharmacophores are obtained from a molecular dynamics simulation of a protein-ligand complex. In this notebook we will obtain pharmacophores from a 10 ns trajectory of the ERalpha. \n",
    "\n",
    "Different methods have been proposed for obtaining pharmacophores from a molecular dynamics, some are very simple and some more complex. We will explore different methods implemented in OpenPharmacophore."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "id": "daed027f-eacb-4cc2-af5b-a165cf842708",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "%matplotlib inline\n",
    "from openpharmacophore.dynophore import Dynophore\n",
    "from IPython.display import Image\n",
    "import mdtraj as md"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ace85cf2-2b7c-4f80-a5ee-4745368130b2",
   "metadata": {
    "tags": []
   },
   "source": [
    "## Pharmacophores from a molecular dynamics trajectory"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "93110309-62a3-4390-9b7a-f4be869c3569",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "First we load the trajectory file with mdtraj."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "id": "eb851c28-fc49-4080-a459-311ec24e0aa9",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "<mdtraj.Trajectory with 1000 frames, 27425 atoms, 8028 residues, and unitcells>\n",
      "<mdtraj.Topology with 4 chains, 8028 residues, 27425 atoms, 19689 bonds>\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "traj_file = \"../../data/trajectories/ERalpha.h5\"\n",
    "traj = md.load(traj_file)\n",
    "print(traj)\n",
    "print(traj.topology)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "860ca9f2-b4bd-46ad-99ba-aa70a2d3ac4a",
   "metadata": {
    "jp-MarkdownHeadingCollapsed": true,
    "tags": []
   },
   "source": [
    "### Pharmacophores from the first and last frame only\n",
    "\n",
    "A very simple way of obtaining pharmacophores from a trajectory is just to extract a pharmacophore from the first and las frame of the trajectory.\n",
    "\n",
    "To work with trajectories we will use the Dynophore class. The constructor expects a trajectory object. This class is different from the other pharmacophore classes.\n",
    "\n",
    "First, we will use the first_and_last_pharmacophore method. We can get a list of all extracted pharmacophores from the trajectory with the attribute pharmacophores."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "id": "c00c27bf-0730-4251-95e4-f5babff938d5",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "[StructuredBasedPharmacophore(n_elements: 9),\n",
       " StructuredBasedPharmacophore(n_elements: 6)]"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 6,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "dynophore = Dynophore(traj)\n",
    "dynophore.first_and_last_pharmacophore()\n",
    "dynophore.pharmacophores"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "id": "1eb759e4-3367-4a28-84fb-83dffc27aa53",
   "metadata": {},

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "4aaa9841-13b2-4a7d-a9d2-7997c094e913",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We can see that the pharmacophore model obtained from the initial frame differs from the last frame pharmacophore."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "877d3e98-e2d4-4615-a16e-9b6d79d20224",
   "metadata": {
    "tags": []
   },
   "source": [
    "### Pharmacophore Analysis\n",
    "\n",
    "To do a bit of a more sophisticated analysis, we can start by obtaining a pharmacophore model for each frame of the trajectory. We can use the pharmacophores_from_frames method which expects a list of frame indices. This can take a while. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "963ca2e1-e678-4a19-abdb-49e5d17bab50",
   "metadata": {
    "tags": []
   },
   "source": [
    "### Get Pharmacophores for each frame of the trajectory"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "id": "e66eb017-5311-44a3-b2bd-6b7f75481457",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "application/vnd.jupyter.widget-view+json": {
       "model_id": "78c6bd41ca8b43d9bba18a80950689b0",
       "version_major": 2,
       "version_minor": 0
      },
      "text/plain": [
       "  0%|          | 0/1000 [00:00<?, ?it/s]"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "dynophore = Dynophore(traj)\n",
    "frames = list(range(0, traj.n_frames))\n",
    "dynophore.pharmacophores_from_frames(frames, load_ligand=True)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "id": "81667f13-fda2-4862-809a-096f4ed6b505",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Number of pharmacophores 1000\n",
      "\n",
      "[StructuredBasedPharmacophore(n_elements: 9), StructuredBasedPharmacophore(n_elements: 6), StructuredBasedPharmacophore(n_elements: 7)]\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "print(f\"Number of pharmacophores {len(dynophore.pharmacophores)}\\n\")\n",
    "# Print first three pharmacophores\n",
    "print(dynophore.pharmacophores[0:3])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "3c4f338b-7875-4bd7-bd07-8f1a46b43bcf",
   "metadata": {
    "tags": []
   },
   "source": [
    "### Get all unique pharmacophoric points"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "097e078b-fde7-4786-9195-336b707c1c8e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2ef0eca6-f3ff-4774-9a65-c0de7e1e2e49",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "All unique pharmacophoric points are stored in a list that can be accessed by the attribute unique_pharmacophoric_points"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "id": "1ae21cd6-61f7-45b5-9d50-5545c70985ca",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Number of unique points is 19\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "unique_points = dynophore.unique_pharmacophoric_points\n",
    "print(f\"Number of unique points is {len(unique_points)}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "57c381fc-59b5-464b-a885-e5e848f40ec8",
   "metadata": {
    "tags": []
   },
   "source": [
    "### Derive a pharmacophore model from the most frequent points"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "690139a5-95d3-492e-bcaf-ffa004eafc57",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Another method to get a pharmacophore from a MD trajectory is to get a single pharmacophore model with the points that are above a certain frequency value. Here we get a pharmacophore model with all the points that have a frequency higher than 50%. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "id": "fba82974-2709-4c07-810f-f460cab39385",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Pharmacophore(n_elements: 5)\n",
      "[HbAcceptorSphere(center: (25.0894, 20.0576, 23.4682); radius: 1.0), HbAcceptorSphere(center: (34.3315, 14.9745, 25.9307); radius: 1.0), HbDonorSphere(center: (25.1247, 19.8936, 23.3244); radius: 1.0), HbDonorSphere(center: (34.0505, 14.3638, 26.2629); radius: 1.0), HydrophobicitySphere(center: (27.0897, 18.2293, 23.3299); radius: 1.0)]\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "freq_threshold = 0.5\n",
    "frequency_pharmacophore = dynophore.pharmacophore_by_frequency(freq_threshold)\n",
    "print(frequency_pharmacophore)\n",
    "print(frequency_pharmacophore.elements)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "cd88566a-e618-42c4-bad2-d1718a9ba86d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Analyze frequency of all unique points"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "3a64260d-558d-4e25-b227-7a1c32b75c39",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We can also plot the frequency of the pharmacophoric points across the trajectory. This way we can have an idea of the freqency through time."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 17,
   "id": "b425d4f3-cf39-44ff-8201-170cb4a9fa4d",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 720x504 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "<AxesSubplot:xlabel='Timesteps', ylabel='Count'>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 17,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Set the frequency threshold to a high value (40%) so that the plot doesn't look too crowded.\n",
    "\n",
    "freq_threshold = 0.5\n",
    "dynophore.point_frequency_plot(0.4)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "aad40487-2427-44e7-902e-3335a7edce07",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We can create a pharmacophore from this unique pharmacophoric points"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 18,
   "id": "32a25a45-ff9e-4095-9d53-4f3f63985565",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
